This adds the class `JSONEditor.Formatter` that allows the developers to customize strings that are supposed to be displayed to the end-user (i.e the user filling the form on his browser).

To to so, the developer passes a `format` callback to the JSONEditor constructor that will be called with two parameters:
- <string> `key`: The id of the message to display
- <array> (optional) `variables`: An array of string (explained bellow)

The callback is supposed to return the string to display. 
If the callback is undefined or returns undefined/null, the default text for the given key will be used.

Default messages are stored in the object `JSONEditor.defaults.strings` in `default.js`. Every key is documented to inform the user how the `variables`array will be populated.

_Example use:_

``` js
new JSONEditor(document.body, {
  schema: {
    type: "object",
    properties: {
      test: {
        type: "string",
        maxLength: 10,
        minLength: 1
      }
    }
  },
  // With this callback, the default messages will always be displayed, except when the error concerns
  // a string's min length
  format: function(key, variables) {
    // By reading defaults.js, I know that variables[0] is the number of minimum characters for the value
    // to validate the schema
    if(key === "error_minLength") return "Minimum characters: " + variables[0];
    return undefined
  }
})
```

This is a pretty simple string customization but it is better than nothing. This allows developers to translate keys and customize them.

I only extracted the text from `validator.js` for now. But editors are also passed an instance of `JSONEditor.Formatter` stored in `this.formater`. 
To add a string key, add it in `JSONEditor.defaults.string` in `defaults.js` and replace it in the editor code with `this.formatter.format('<key here>', [<variables here>])`

Later we could provide several default key sets based on languages, and provide the title of the schema path that failed being validated for further customization.

Note: The expected default value should match the first type in the types array.

